const SUBJECTS_VIVA_QUESTIONS = [
// ═══ Electrical Circuit 1 (Q1-Q13) ═══
{id:1,topic:"ckt1",q:"What is a node in circuit analysis?",ans:"A node is a point in a circuit where two or more circuit elements are connected. A <strong>principal node</strong> (essential node) connects three or more elements. Nodal analysis uses KCL at each independent node. The number of independent KCL equations = (number of essential nodes − 1)."},
{id:2,topic:"ckt1",q:"What is a loop and a mesh?",ans:"A <strong>loop</strong> is any closed path in a circuit. A <strong>mesh</strong> is a loop that does not contain any other loop within it (smallest possible loop). Mesh analysis applies KVL to each mesh. Number of independent mesh equations = b − n + 1 (branches − nodes + 1)."},
{id:3,topic:"ckt1",q:"Explain the voltage divider rule.",ans:"For resistors R₁ and R₂ in series: <strong>V₁ = Vin × R₁/(R₁+R₂)</strong>. Voltage divides proportionally to resistance. Used for biasing, reference voltages, and attenuation. Only accurate when no significant load current is drawn from the output."},
{id:4,topic:"ckt1",q:"Explain the current divider rule.",ans:"For resistors R₁ and R₂ in parallel: <strong>I₁ = Itotal × R₂/(R₁+R₂)</strong>. Current divides inversely proportional to resistance — more current flows through the lower resistance. For N equal resistors: each carries Itotal/N."},
{id:5,topic:"ckt1",q:"What is source transformation?",ans:"Source transformation converts between a voltage source with series resistance and a current source with parallel resistance. <strong>Vs with Rs ↔ Is with Rp</strong> where Is = Vs/Rs and Rp = Rs. This simplifies circuit analysis. Only applies to practical (non-ideal) sources."},
{id:6,topic:"ckt1",q:"What is linearity in circuits?",ans:"A circuit is linear if it satisfies <strong>superposition</strong> (response to sum of inputs = sum of individual responses) and <strong>homogeneity</strong> (scaling input by k scales output by k). Linear elements: R, L, C (ideal). Nonlinear: diodes, transistors. Most circuit theorems only apply to linear circuits."},
{id:7,topic:"ckt1",q:"Explain capacitors in series and parallel.",ans:"<strong>Series:</strong> 1/Ceq = 1/C₁ + 1/C₂ + 1/C₃ (total capacitance decreases, voltage divides). <strong>Parallel:</strong> Ceq = C₁ + C₂ + C₃ (total capacitance increases, same voltage). Opposite behavior to resistors — series reduces, parallel increases capacitance."},
{id:8,topic:"ckt1",q:"Explain inductors in series and parallel.",ans:"<strong>Series:</strong> Leq = L₁ + L₂ (assuming no mutual coupling). <strong>Parallel:</strong> 1/Leq = 1/L₁ + 1/L₂. With mutual inductance M: Series-aiding: Leq = L₁ + L₂ + 2M. Series-opposing: Leq = L₁ + L₂ − 2M. Same behavior as resistors."},
{id:9,topic:"ckt1",q:"What is the initial and final value theorem?",ans:"<strong>Initial value:</strong> f(0⁺) = lim(s→∞) sF(s) — gives the value immediately after t=0. <strong>Final value:</strong> f(∞) = lim(s→0) sF(s) — gives the steady-state value. Final value theorem only valid if all poles of sF(s) are in the left half of s-plane (stable system)."},
{id:10,topic:"ckt1",q:"What is the step response of an RC circuit?",ans:"When a step voltage V₀ is applied to an RC series circuit: <strong>vc(t) = V₀(1 − e^(−t/RC))</strong> (charging). The voltage rises exponentially with time constant τ = RC. At t = τ: vc = 0.632V₀. At t = 5τ: vc ≈ 0.993V₀ (effectively fully charged). Current: i(t) = (V₀/R)e^(−t/RC)."},
{id:11,topic:"ckt1",q:"What is the natural and forced response?",ans:"<strong>Natural response:</strong> the circuit's response due to initial stored energy (IC/IL at t=0), without any external source. Decays exponentially. <strong>Forced response:</strong> the steady-state response due to the external source. <strong>Complete response = Natural + Forced</strong> (transient + steady-state)."},
{id:12,topic:"ckt1",q:"What is wye-delta transformation used for?",ans:"Wye-delta (Y-Δ) transformation converts between star and delta configurations when a circuit cannot be simplified using series-parallel combinations alone. <strong>Bridge circuits</strong> (like Wheatstone bridge) require Y-Δ transformation for analysis. Formulas relate each delta resistor to the three star resistors."},
{id:13,topic:"ckt1",q:"What is the concept of equivalent circuits?",ans:"An equivalent circuit replaces a complex network with a simpler one that has identical terminal behavior (same V-I relationship). Examples: Thevenin (Vth + Rth), Norton (IN || RN), series/parallel combinations. Internal structure differs, but external behavior is identical. Essential for simplifying analysis."},

// ═══ Electrical Circuit 2 (Q14-Q26) ═══
{id:14,topic:"ckt2",q:"What is AC steady-state analysis?",ans:"AC steady-state analysis finds the response of a circuit to sinusoidal excitation after all transients have died out. Uses <strong>phasor representation</strong> of voltages and currents. Impedances: ZR = R, ZL = jωL, ZC = 1/jωC. All standard circuit theorems apply using complex impedances. Transforms differential equations into algebraic."},
{id:15,topic:"ckt2",q:"What are coupled circuits?",ans:"Coupled circuits have mutual inductance (M) between inductors due to shared magnetic flux. <strong>M = k√(L₁L₂)</strong>, where k is coupling coefficient (0–1). Dot convention: current entering dotted terminals → fluxes add. Coupled circuits are the basis of transformers. Analysis includes self and mutual impedances."},
{id:16,topic:"ckt2",q:"What is a two-port network?",ans:"A two-port network has an input port (1) and output port (2). Characterized by parameters relating V₁, I₁, V₂, I₂: <strong>Z-parameters</strong> (open-circuit), <strong>Y-parameters</strong> (short-circuit), <strong>h-parameters</strong> (hybrid — for BJTs), <strong>ABCD</strong> (transmission — for cascaded networks). Each set fully describes the network."},
{id:17,topic:"ckt2",q:"What is the frequency response of a circuit?",ans:"Frequency response shows how a circuit's gain and phase change with frequency. Plotted as <strong>Bode plot</strong> (magnitude in dB and phase vs log frequency). Determined by the transfer function H(jω). Poles cause −20 dB/decade roll-off and −90° phase shift. Zeros cause +20 dB/decade and +90° phase shift."},
{id:18,topic:"ckt2",q:"Explain series and parallel resonance.",ans:"<strong>Series resonance:</strong> Z = R (minimum), I = V/R (maximum), XL = XC. <strong>Parallel resonance:</strong> Z = R (maximum), I from source is minimum, circulating current in tank. Both occur at fr = 1/(2π√LC). Series: voltage magnification (QVs). Parallel: current magnification (QIs). Q = fr/BW."},
{id:19,topic:"ckt2",q:"What is the Fourier series and its application in circuits?",ans:"Fourier series decomposes any periodic waveform into DC + fundamental + harmonics: f(t) = a₀/2 + Σ(aₙcos(nωt) + bₙsin(nωt)). Application: analyze circuit response to non-sinusoidal inputs by finding response to each harmonic separately (using superposition). Total response = sum of individual harmonic responses."},
{id:20,topic:"ckt2",q:"What is the Laplace transform in circuit analysis?",ans:"Laplace transform converts time-domain functions to s-domain: F(s) = ∫f(t)e^(−st)dt. <strong>Simplifies circuit analysis</strong> by converting differential equations to algebraic. Impedances: R, sL, 1/sC. Initial conditions included as sources. Inverse Laplace gives time-domain solution. Essential for transient analysis."},
{id:21,topic:"ckt2",q:"What are poles and zeros of a transfer function?",ans:"<strong>Poles:</strong> values of s where H(s) → ∞ (denominator = 0). Determine natural frequencies and stability. <strong>Zeros:</strong> values of s where H(s) = 0 (numerator = 0). Create nulls in response. All poles must be in left half of s-plane for a stable system. Pole-zero plot completely characterizes the system."},
{id:22,topic:"ckt2",q:"What is the convolution integral?",ans:"Convolution finds the output of a linear system: y(t) = ∫h(τ)x(t−τ)dτ = x(t) * h(t), where h(t) is the impulse response. In frequency domain: Y(s) = H(s)X(s) (multiplication replaces convolution). This is a fundamental result linking time and frequency domain analysis."},
{id:23,topic:"ckt2",q:"What is the maximum power transfer for AC circuits?",ans:"For AC circuits, maximum power transfer occurs when <strong>ZL = ZS*</strong> (load impedance = conjugate of source impedance). This means RL = RS and XL = −XS. If only RL can be varied: RL = |ZS| = √(RS² + XS²). Maximum power = |Vth|²/(8RS)."},
{id:24,topic:"ckt2",q:"What are network functions?",ans:"Network functions relate terminal quantities in the s-domain. <strong>Driving point impedance:</strong> Z(s) = V(s)/I(s) at the same port. <strong>Transfer function:</strong> H(s) = output/input at different ports. For passive networks, all poles and zeros must satisfy specific realizability conditions (positive real functions)."},
{id:25,topic:"ckt2",q:"What is the concept of duality in circuits?",ans:"Duality maps every element and quantity to its dual counterpart: V ↔ I, R ↔ G, L ↔ C, Series ↔ Parallel, KVL ↔ KCL, Mesh ↔ Node, Thevenin ↔ Norton, Short ↔ Open. The dual circuit has the same mathematical form with interchanged quantities. Useful for deriving new results from known ones."},
{id:26,topic:"ckt2",q:"What is network synthesis?",ans:"Network synthesis designs a network that realizes a given network function (transfer function or impedance). Starting from specifications (cutoff frequency, roll-off, etc.), the function is derived, then a physical circuit is constructed using standard topologies (Foster, Cauer forms). Opposite of network analysis."},

// ═══ Machine 1 (Q27-Q40) ═══
{id:27,topic:"m1",q:"What is the principle of DC machines?",ans:"DC machines work on <strong>electromagnetic principles</strong>. Generator: conductor moving in magnetic field → induced EMF (Faraday's law). Motor: current-carrying conductor in magnetic field → force (F = BIL, Lorentz force). The commutator converts AC (in armature) to DC (at terminals) for generators, and vice versa for motors."},
{id:28,topic:"m1",q:"Explain the construction of a DC machine.",ans:"<strong>Stator:</strong> Yoke (frame), pole cores, pole shoes, field windings, interpoles. <strong>Rotor (Armature):</strong> laminated core, armature winding (in slots), commutator, brushes. <strong>Commutator:</strong> segmented copper cylinder — converts AC to DC. <strong>Brushes:</strong> carbon/graphite — make sliding contact with commutator."},
{id:29,topic:"m1",q:"What is the EMF equation of a DC generator?",ans:"<strong>E = PΦNZ/(60A)</strong>, where P = number of poles, Φ = flux per pole (Wb), N = speed (RPM), Z = total armature conductors, A = number of parallel paths. For lap winding: A = P. For wave winding: A = 2. EMF is proportional to speed and flux."},
{id:30,topic:"m1",q:"What are the types of DC generators?",ans:"<strong>1. Separately excited:</strong> field winding supplied by an external source.\n<strong>2. Self-excited:</strong> field supplied from own armature.\n  a. <strong>Shunt:</strong> field parallel to armature (most common).\n  b. <strong>Series:</strong> field in series with armature.\n  c. <strong>Compound:</strong> both shunt and series field windings (cumulative or differential)."},
{id:31,topic:"m1",q:"What is armature reaction in DC machines?",ans:"Armature reaction is the effect of armature current's magnetic field on the main field. Effects: <strong>1. Cross-magnetizing:</strong> distorts the main field. <strong>2. Demagnetizing:</strong> weakens the main field (in generators). <strong>3. Shifts magnetic neutral axis</strong> (forward in generators, backward in motors). Compensated by interpoles and compensating windings."},
{id:32,topic:"m1",q:"What is commutation?",ans:"Commutation is the reversal of current direction in an armature coil as it passes through the magnetic neutral axis. Ideal: <strong>linear commutation</strong> (current reverses uniformly). Poor commutation causes <strong>sparking at brushes</strong>. Improved by: interpoles (commutating poles), resistance commutation (carbon brushes), and proper brush positioning."},
{id:33,topic:"m1",q:"Explain DC motor speed control methods.",ans:"<strong>1. Armature voltage control:</strong> V varies, Φ constant. Speed below base speed. Best method (constant torque).\n<strong>2. Field weakening:</strong> reduce Φ. Speed above base speed (constant power).\n<strong>3. Armature resistance control:</strong> add external resistance. Lossy, poor regulation. Simple but inefficient.\nModern: PWM controllers for armature voltage."},
{id:34,topic:"m1",q:"What is the torque equation of a DC motor?",ans:"<strong>T = PΦIaZ/(2πA) = KaΦIa</strong>. Torque is proportional to flux and armature current. For series motor: T ∝ Ia² (at low current, before saturation). For shunt motor: T ∝ Ia (constant flux). Starting torque = KaΦIa(start), which can be very high."},
{id:35,topic:"m1",q:"Why is a DC series motor never run without load?",ans:"In a series motor, flux Φ ∝ Ia. At no load, Ia is very small → flux is very small → speed N ∝ V/Φ becomes dangerously high (theoretically infinite). The motor <strong>runs away</strong> and can self-destruct. Always use mechanical coupling (gears/belt) — never pulley+belt alone. Shunt and compound motors are safe at no load."},
{id:36,topic:"m1",q:"Explain the characteristics of a DC shunt motor.",ans:"<strong>Speed characteristic:</strong> approximately constant speed (slightly drooping) — N = (V−IaRa)/(KΦ). <strong>Torque characteristic:</strong> T ∝ Ia (linear). <strong>Speed-torque:</strong> nearly flat speed with increasing torque. Shunt motors are used where constant speed is needed: lathes, drills, blowers, conveyors."},
{id:37,topic:"m1",q:"What are losses in a DC machine?",ans:"<strong>1. Copper losses:</strong> I²R in armature, field, brush contact. Variable with load.\n<strong>2. Iron (core) losses:</strong> Hysteresis + Eddy current in armature core. Approximately constant.\n<strong>3. Mechanical losses:</strong> Friction (bearings, brushes) + Windage (air resistance). Approximately constant.\n<strong>4. Stray losses:</strong> miscellaneous (1-2% of output)."},
{id:38,topic:"m1",q:"What is the Swinburne's test?",ans:"Swinburne's test determines DC machine losses by running it as a motor at no-load. It measures: no-load current I₀, field current If, and input power. <strong>Core + mechanical losses = VIa₀ − Ia₀²Ra</strong>. Efficiency at any load can be predicted without actually loading the machine. Cannot detect commutation problems."},
{id:39,topic:"m1",q:"What is the Hopkinson's (back-to-back) test?",ans:"Hopkinson's test uses two identical DC machines coupled mechanically — one as motor, one as generator. The generator feeds the motor. Only losses need to be supplied from the source. <strong>Full-load test with minimum power consumption</strong>. Determines full-load efficiency, temperature rise, and commutation performance."},
{id:40,topic:"m1",q:"What are the applications of DC motors?",ans:"<strong>Series:</strong> Electric traction (trains, EVs), cranes, hoists — needs high starting torque.\n<strong>Shunt:</strong> Machine tools, centrifugal pumps, fans — needs constant speed.\n<strong>Compound:</strong> Rolling mills, elevators, presses — needs high starting torque + speed regulation.\n<strong>PMDC:</strong> Small appliances, toys, automotive accessories."},

// ═══ Machine 2 (Q41-Q54) ═══
{id:41,topic:"m2",q:"What is the principle of a three-phase induction motor?",ans:"When three-phase supply is connected to the stator, it creates a <strong>Rotating Magnetic Field (RMF)</strong> at synchronous speed Ns = 120f/P. This RMF induces EMF in the rotor conductors (Faraday's law). The induced current in the rotor interacts with the RMF to produce torque (F = BIL). The rotor rotates in the direction of the RMF at speed Nr < Ns."},
{id:42,topic:"m2",q:"Explain the concept of rotating magnetic field.",ans:"When three-phase currents (displaced by 120°) flow through three-phase stator windings (physically displaced by 120°), they produce a <strong>resultant magnetic field that rotates at constant speed</strong>. Speed = Ns = 120f/P RPM. Magnitude = 1.5 × Φm (constant). This rotating field is key to all AC motor operation."},
{id:43,topic:"m2",q:"What is the equivalent circuit of an induction motor?",ans:"Similar to a transformer: <strong>Stator:</strong> R₁ + jX₁ (winding impedance). <strong>Core:</strong> Rc || jXm (loss and magnetizing). <strong>Rotor (referred to stator):</strong> R₂'/s + jX₂'. The term R₂'/s = R₂' + R₂'(1−s)/s, where R₂' is rotor copper loss and R₂'(1−s)/s represents mechanical power developed."},
{id:44,topic:"m2",q:"What is the torque-slip characteristic?",ans:"Torque vs slip curve: At s=0 (synchronous speed): T=0. As slip increases: T increases linearly (stable operating region). At s=sm (typically 0.1-0.2): T reaches maximum (<strong>breakdown torque</strong>, Tmax ≈ 2-3× rated). Beyond sm: T decreases. At s=1 (standstill): T = starting torque. Motor operates stably only when s < sm."},
{id:45,topic:"m2",q:"Explain the speed control of induction motors.",ans:"<strong>1. Frequency control (VFD):</strong> Best method. N ∝ f. V/f ratio maintained constant.\n<strong>2. Pole changing:</strong> Discrete speeds (Ns = 120f/P).\n<strong>3. Stator voltage control:</strong> T ∝ V². Limited range.\n<strong>4. Rotor resistance control:</strong> For wound rotor only. Lossy but simple.\n<strong>5. Slip power recovery (Kramer/Scherbius):</strong> Efficient for wound rotor."},
{id:46,topic:"m2",q:"What are the starting methods for induction motors?",ans:"<strong>1. DOL (Direct On Line):</strong> For small motors (<5 HP). Starting current = 5-8× rated.\n<strong>2. Star-Delta:</strong> Reduces voltage to V/√3. Current = 1/3 of DOL. For motors designed for delta operation.\n<strong>3. Autotransformer:</strong> Adjustable reduced voltage. Current ∝ (tap ratio)².\n<strong>4. Soft starter:</strong> Electronic, gradual voltage increase.\n<strong>5. VFD:</strong> Best — controlled frequency and voltage."},
{id:47,topic:"m2",q:"What is a synchronous motor and why is it not self-starting?",ans:"A synchronous motor has DC-excited rotor that must rotate at exactly Ns = 120f/P. It is <strong>not self-starting</strong> because the stator RMF rotates at Ns while the rotor is stationary. The alternating torque on the rotor averages to zero. Starting methods: damper windings (start as induction motor), auxiliary motor, or VFD."},
{id:48,topic:"m2",q:"Explain the V-curve of a synchronous motor.",ans:"V-curves plot armature current (Ia) vs field current (If) at constant load. At <strong>normal excitation</strong>: unity PF, minimum Ia. <strong>Under-excited:</strong> lagging PF (acts as inductor). <strong>Over-excited:</strong> leading PF (acts as capacitor). Over-excited synchronous motor = <strong>synchronous condenser</strong> — used for power factor correction."},
{id:49,topic:"m2",q:"What is a synchronous condenser?",ans:"A synchronous condenser is an <strong>over-excited synchronous motor running at no load</strong>. It draws leading current, acting like a large capacitor. Used for <strong>power factor correction</strong> and voltage regulation in power systems. Advantages: stepless reactive power control, voltage support. Disadvantages: expensive, moving parts, losses."},
{id:50,topic:"m2",q:"What is an alternator (synchronous generator)?",ans:"An alternator converts mechanical energy to AC. Rotor has DC field winding. Stator has three-phase armature winding. <strong>EMF equation: E = 4.44fNΦKw</strong>. Frequency: f = PN/120. Types: Salient pole (hydro — low speed, many poles) and Cylindrical (turbo — high speed, 2 or 4 poles). Load sharing by governor and AVR."},
{id:51,topic:"m2",q:"What are the parallel operation conditions for alternators?",ans:"<strong>1. Same voltage magnitude</strong> (adjusted by field excitation/AVR).\n<strong>2. Same frequency</strong> (adjusted by prime mover/governor).\n<strong>3. Same phase sequence</strong> (R-Y-B matching).\n<strong>4. In phase</strong> (synchronized using synchroscope or dark lamp method).\nViolation causes large circulating currents, transients, and potential damage."},
{id:52,topic:"m2",q:"What is the voltage regulation of an alternator?",ans:"Voltage regulation = <strong>(E₀ − V)/V × 100%</strong>, where E₀ = no-load terminal voltage, V = full-load terminal voltage. Depends on load PF: Lagging PF → positive regulation (voltage drops). Unity PF → small positive. Leading PF → negative regulation (voltage rises, Ferranti-like effect)."},
{id:53,topic:"m2",q:"What is the synchronizing power coefficient?",ans:"Synchronizing power = <strong>Ps = dP/dδ = (VE₀cosδ)/Xs</strong>, where δ is the load angle. It measures the machine's ability to remain in synchronism. Maximum power transfer at δ = 90°. For stable operation: δ < 90° (synchronizing power is positive). At δ = 90°: Ps = 0 → stability limit."},
{id:54,topic:"m2",q:"What is hunting in synchronous machines?",ans:"Hunting is the oscillation of the rotor around the synchronous speed due to sudden load changes. The rotor swings back and forth, causing fluctuating speed and power. Damped by <strong>damper windings</strong> (short-circuited bars in rotor pole faces). Excessive hunting can cause loss of synchronism. Also called <strong>phase swinging</strong>."},

// ═══ Transmission & Distribution (Q55-Q67) ═══
{id:55,topic:"tnd",q:"Why is power transmitted at high voltage?",ans:"Power loss = I²R. For same power P: I = P/(√3 × V × cosφ). Higher voltage → lower current → <strong>much lower I²R losses</strong>. Also: smaller conductor cross-section needed (cheaper), less voltage drop. Example: transmitting at 400kV vs 11kV reduces current by 36× and losses by 1300×. Economics favor high voltage for long distances."},
{id:56,topic:"tnd",q:"What is the ABCD parameter model of a transmission line?",ans:"The ABCD (transmission) parameters relate sending and receiving end quantities: <strong>[Vs; Is] = [A B; C D] × [Vr; Ir]</strong>. For short line: A=D=1, B=Z, C=0. For medium line (π model): A=D=1+YZ/2, B=Z, C=Y(1+YZ/4). AD−BC=1 always. Used for voltage regulation and efficiency calculations."},
{id:57,topic:"tnd",q:"What are the types of transmission line models?",ans:"<strong>Short line (<80 km):</strong> Series impedance only (R+jX). Capacitance negligible.\n<strong>Medium line (80-250 km):</strong> Nominal π or T model. Lumped capacitance.\n<strong>Long line (>250 km):</strong> Distributed parameter model. Uses hyperbolic functions. Accounts for wave propagation along the line."},
{id:58,topic:"tnd",q:"What is the surge impedance loading (SIL)?",ans:"SIL is the load at which the line's reactive power generation (from capacitance) equals reactive power absorption (by inductance). <strong>SIL = V²/Zc</strong>, where Zc = √(L/C) is the surge impedance. At SIL: voltage is flat along the line, no reactive power flow. Below SIL: voltage rises. Above SIL: voltage drops."},
{id:59,topic:"tnd",q:"What is the Ferranti effect?",ans:"On long, lightly loaded lines, the <strong>receiving-end voltage exceeds the sending-end voltage</strong> due to the capacitive charging current effect. The line capacitance provides reactive power that raises the voltage. More pronounced on longer lines and lower loads. Controlled by shunt reactors or SVCs at the receiving end."},
{id:60,topic:"tnd",q:"What are ACSR conductors?",ans:"ACSR (Aluminium Conductor Steel Reinforced) is the most common conductor for overhead transmission. <strong>Core:</strong> galvanized steel strands for strength. <strong>Outer layers:</strong> aluminium strands for conductivity. Combines the strength of steel with the conductivity of aluminium. Lighter and cheaper than copper. Typical size: 100-800 mm²."},
{id:61,topic:"tnd",q:"What is corona and how to reduce it?",ans:"Corona is ionization of air around HV conductors when surface gradient > 30 kV/cm. <strong>Effects:</strong> power loss, radio interference, audible noise, ozone. <strong>Reduction:</strong> 1. Increase conductor diameter (bundled conductors). 2. Increase spacing. 3. Use smooth, clean conductors. Critical voltage: Vc = m₀m₁δ × 21.2 × r × ln(D/r) kV."},
{id:62,topic:"tnd",q:"What is a distribution system?",ans:"Distribution system delivers power from substations to consumers. <strong>Primary distribution:</strong> 11kV or 33kV to distribution transformers. <strong>Secondary distribution:</strong> 400V/230V to consumers. Topologies: Radial (simplest, least reliable), Ring (better reliability), Network (mesh — most reliable, complex). Underground or overhead."},
{id:63,topic:"tnd",q:"What is sag in overhead lines?",ans:"Sag is the vertical distance between the highest point of the conductor (support) and the lowest point (midpoint). <strong>Sag = wL²/(8T)</strong>, where w = weight per unit length, L = span, T = tension. Sag increases with temperature (conductor expands) and ice loading. Clearance = tower height − sag − safety margin."},
{id:64,topic:"tnd",q:"What is string efficiency of insulators?",ans:"String efficiency = (Voltage across string)/(n × Voltage across nearest disc) × 100%. Ideally 100%, meaning equal voltage distribution. In practice, the disc nearest the conductor has the highest voltage due to stray capacitance. Improved by grading (different capacitance discs) or guard rings."},
{id:65,topic:"tnd",q:"What is the purpose of ground wire in transmission lines?",ans:"Ground wire (earth wire/shield wire) is installed above the phase conductors. <strong>Purpose:</strong> 1. Lightning protection — intercepts lightning strokes. 2. Reduces induced voltage from lightning. 3. Provides fault current return path. Usually made of galvanized steel or ACSR. Sometimes contains fiber optic cable (OPGW) for communication."},
{id:66,topic:"tnd",q:"What is a cable and its construction?",ans:"A power cable has: <strong>1. Conductor</strong> (copper or aluminium). <strong>2. Insulation</strong> (XLPE — most common, PVC, paper). <strong>3. Metallic sheath</strong> (lead or aluminium — moisture barrier). <strong>4. Armour</strong> (steel wire — mechanical protection). <strong>5. Outer jacket</strong> (PVC/PE — corrosion protection). Used for underground/submarine transmission."},
{id:67,topic:"tnd",q:"What is the per-unit system in power systems?",ans:"Per-unit (pu) = actual value / base value. <strong>Base values:</strong> Choose Sbase (MVA) and Vbase (kV), then Ibase = Sbase/(√3×Vbase), Zbase = Vbase²/Sbase. <strong>Advantages:</strong> eliminates transformer turns ratio, simplifies calculations across voltage levels, similar equipment has similar pu impedances, easy to spot abnormal values."},

// ═══ Power System Analysis (Q68-Q80) ═══
{id:68,topic:"psa",q:"What is load flow analysis?",ans:"Load flow determines <strong>steady-state bus voltages, line currents, and power flows</strong>. Bus types: Slack (V and δ specified), PV/Generator (P and V specified), PQ/Load (P and Q specified). Methods: <strong>Gauss-Seidel</strong> (simple, slow), <strong>Newton-Raphson</strong> (fast, widely used), <strong>Fast Decoupled</strong> (simplified NR for large systems)."},
{id:69,topic:"psa",q:"What is symmetrical fault analysis?",ans:"Symmetrical (three-phase) fault: all three phases shorted simultaneously. Most severe fault (~5% occurrence). Fault current: <strong>If = Vf/Zf</strong>, where Vf = pre-fault voltage, Zf = fault impedance (Thevenin impedance). Used for circuit breaker rating. Analysis uses bus impedance matrix (Zbus) or Thevenin equivalent."},
{id:70,topic:"psa",q:"What are symmetrical components?",ans:"Symmetrical components decompose unbalanced three-phase quantities into three balanced sets: <strong>Positive sequence</strong> (a-b-c rotation — normal), <strong>Negative sequence</strong> (a-c-b — reverse rotation), <strong>Zero sequence</strong> (all in phase). Used for unsymmetrical fault analysis. Each component has its own impedance network. Operator a = 1∠120°."},
{id:71,topic:"psa",q:"What is the swing equation?",ans:"<strong>M(d²δ/dt²) = Pa = Pm − Pe</strong>, where M = inertia constant, δ = rotor angle, Pa = accelerating power, Pm = mechanical power, Pe = electrical power. Describes the dynamic behavior of a synchronous machine. Used for transient stability analysis. If δ increases unboundedly, the machine loses synchronism."},
{id:72,topic:"psa",q:"What is the equal area criterion?",ans:"The equal area criterion determines transient stability <strong>without solving the swing equation</strong>. For a sudden disturbance: the system is stable if the <strong>accelerating area (A1) ≤ maximum decelerating area (A2)</strong> on the P-δ curve. If A1 > A2: unstable (machine pulls out of synchronism). Quick graphical method for single-machine infinite bus."},
{id:73,topic:"psa",q:"What is the Ybus and Zbus matrix?",ans:"<strong>Ybus</strong> (bus admittance matrix): diagonal elements = sum of admittances connected to bus i. Off-diagonal yij = −admittance between bus i and j. Used in load flow. <strong>Zbus</strong> (bus impedance matrix) = inverse of Ybus. Used in fault analysis. Sparse Ybus is preferred for large systems."},
{id:74,topic:"psa",q:"What is economic dispatch?",ans:"Economic dispatch minimizes the <strong>total fuel cost</strong> of generation while meeting load demand. Each generator has a cost function: Ci = ai + biPi + ciPi². Optimal: all units operate at equal incremental cost (λ) = dCi/dPi. Constraint: ΣPi = PD + PL (demand + losses). Solved by lambda iteration or gradient methods."},
{id:75,topic:"psa",q:"What is the concept of stability in power systems?",ans:"<strong>1. Steady-state stability:</strong> ability to maintain synchronism under small disturbances. Limited by Pmax = VE/X.\n<strong>2. Transient stability:</strong> maintain synchronism after large disturbances (faults, load rejection). Analyzed by swing equation.\n<strong>3. Dynamic stability:</strong> considering continuous small oscillations with AVR and governor action. Damping of oscillations is key."},
{id:76,topic:"psa",q:"What is a single line diagram (SLD)?",ans:"An SLD is a simplified <strong>schematic representation</strong> of a power system using standard symbols. Shows generators, transformers, transmission lines, loads, circuit breakers, and their interconnections. Impedance data is noted on each element. Used as the starting point for all power system studies (load flow, fault analysis, stability)."},
{id:77,topic:"psa",q:"What is the significance of X/R ratio?",ans:"The X/R ratio of a power system affects: <strong>1. Fault current DC offset</strong> (higher X/R → longer DC transient). 2. Circuit breaker duty. 3. Power factor of fault current. High X/R (typical for HV systems, >15) means the fault current is highly inductive. Affects the rate of current zero crossing for breaker interruption."},
{id:78,topic:"psa",q:"What is optimal power flow (OPF)?",ans:"OPF determines the optimal operating point that minimizes cost (or losses) subject to network constraints: <strong>Power balance, generation limits, voltage limits, line flow limits</strong>. More comprehensive than economic dispatch as it includes network constraints. Solved using linear programming, interior point methods, or AI techniques."},
{id:79,topic:"psa",q:"What is contingency analysis?",ans:"Contingency analysis evaluates the system's ability to withstand the loss of one or more components (N−1 or N−2 contingency). For each contingency: run load flow, check for overloads, voltage violations. <strong>N−1 security:</strong> system must survive loss of any single element. Critical for reliable power system operation and planning."},
{id:80,topic:"psa",q:"What is the power circle diagram?",ans:"The power circle diagram graphically represents the sending and receiving end power of a transmission line. <strong>Center and radius</strong> depend on ABCD parameters. Used to determine: maximum power transfer, stability limit, power factor, and voltage regulation. The sending end circle shows apparent power delivered to the line."},

// ═══ Communication Engineering (Q81-Q93) ═══
{id:81,topic:"comm",q:"What is modulation and why is it needed?",ans:"Modulation impresses information (baseband signal) onto a higher-frequency carrier for transmission. <strong>Need:</strong> 1. Antenna size ∝ wavelength (lower frequency → impractically large antenna). 2. Multiple signals can share the medium (FDM). 3. Better propagation at RF frequencies. Types: AM, FM, PM (analog); ASK, FSK, PSK, QAM (digital)."},
{id:82,topic:"comm",q:"What is AM (Amplitude Modulation)?",ans:"AM varies the carrier amplitude proportionally to the message signal. <strong>s(t) = Ac[1 + mcos(ωmt)]cos(ωct)</strong>. Modulation index m = Am/Ac (0–1). Spectrum: carrier + upper sideband (fc+fm) + lower sideband (fc−fm). Bandwidth = 2fm. Disadvantage: 2/3 power in carrier (wastes power). Simple but inefficient."},
{id:83,topic:"comm",q:"What is FM (Frequency Modulation)?",ans:"FM varies the carrier frequency proportionally to the message signal. <strong>f(t) = fc + kf × m(t)</strong>. Deviation Δf = kf × Am. Modulation index β = Δf/fm. Bandwidth ≈ 2(Δf + fm) (Carson's rule). Advantages over AM: better noise immunity, constant power, better audio quality. Used in FM radio (88–108 MHz)."},
{id:84,topic:"comm",q:"What is the Shannon-Hartley theorem?",ans:"<strong>C = B × log₂(1 + SNR)</strong>, where C = channel capacity (bps), B = bandwidth (Hz), SNR = signal-to-noise ratio. This sets the theoretical maximum data rate for a channel. To increase capacity: increase bandwidth or SNR. No error-free communication beyond C. Foundation of information theory."},
{id:85,topic:"comm",q:"What is the Nyquist criterion for digital communication?",ans:"<strong>Maximum symbol rate = 2B symbols/sec</strong> for a bandwidth B Hz (Nyquist rate). For M-ary signaling: bit rate = 2B × log₂(M) bps. With ISI-free pulse shaping (raised cosine): practical rates approach Nyquist limit. Relates channel bandwidth to maximum data rate."},
{id:86,topic:"comm",q:"What is PCM (Pulse Code Modulation)?",ans:"PCM digitizes analog signals in three steps: <strong>1. Sampling</strong> (at ≥ 2fmax rate). <strong>2. Quantization</strong> (mapping to discrete levels — introduces quantization noise). <strong>3. Encoding</strong> (binary representation). Each sample → n-bit code word. Bit rate = fs × n. Used in digital telephony (8 kHz × 8 bits = 64 kbps)."},
{id:87,topic:"comm",q:"What is SNR (Signal-to-Noise Ratio)?",ans:"SNR = Signal power / Noise power. In dB: <strong>SNR(dB) = 10 log₁₀(Ps/Pn)</strong>. Higher SNR = cleaner signal. For PCM: SNR ≈ 6n + 1.76 dB (n = bits). For FM: SNR improves with higher deviation (wider bandwidth). SNR is the fundamental measure of signal quality."},
{id:88,topic:"comm",q:"What is multiplexing?",ans:"Multiplexing shares a single channel among multiple signals. <strong>FDM:</strong> Each signal uses a different frequency band (analog). <strong>TDM:</strong> Each signal uses a different time slot (digital). <strong>WDM:</strong> Different wavelengths in optical fiber. <strong>CDM:</strong> Different codes (spread spectrum). <strong>OFDM:</strong> Many closely-spaced subcarriers (WiFi, LTE)."},
{id:89,topic:"comm",q:"What is antenna gain?",ans:"Antenna gain is the ratio of radiation intensity in a given direction to that of an isotropic antenna (reference). <strong>G(dBi) = 10 log₁₀(Pmax/Pisotropic)</strong>. Higher gain = more directional beam. Dipole: 2.15 dBi. Yagi: 10–15 dBi. Parabolic dish: 20–45 dBi. Gain increases with antenna size relative to wavelength."},
{id:90,topic:"comm",q:"What is fiber optic communication?",ans:"Fiber optic uses <strong>light pulses through glass/plastic fibers</strong> for communication. Advantages: enormous bandwidth (THz), low loss (0.2 dB/km at 1550nm), immune to EMI, secure, lightweight. Types: Single-mode (long distance, small core 9μm) and Multi-mode (short distance, larger core 50/62.5μm). Components: laser/LED, fiber, photodetector."},
{id:91,topic:"comm",q:"What is the electromagnetic spectrum?",ans:"The EM spectrum ranges from radio waves to gamma rays: <strong>Radio</strong> (kHz–GHz) → <strong>Microwave</strong> (1–300 GHz) → <strong>Infrared</strong> → <strong>Visible light</strong> → <strong>Ultraviolet</strong> → <strong>X-rays</strong> → <strong>Gamma rays</strong>. Communication uses radio (AM/FM, TV), microwave (satellite, radar), infrared (fiber, remote), and visible (fiber optics)."},
{id:92,topic:"comm",q:"What is spread spectrum communication?",ans:"Spread spectrum deliberately spreads the signal over a bandwidth much wider than the minimum needed. Types: <strong>FHSS</strong> (Frequency Hopping) and <strong>DSSS</strong> (Direct Sequence). Advantages: resistance to jamming, low probability of intercept, multiple access (CDMA), multipath resistance. Used in WiFi, Bluetooth, GPS, military."},
{id:93,topic:"comm",q:"What is digital modulation?",ans:"Digital modulation encodes digital data onto a carrier. <strong>ASK:</strong> amplitude varies (simple, noise-sensitive). <strong>FSK:</strong> frequency varies (better noise immunity). <strong>PSK:</strong> phase varies (efficient). <strong>QAM:</strong> both amplitude and phase vary (high spectral efficiency — used in WiFi, LTE). Higher-order → more bits/symbol but more SNR needed."},

// ═══ VLSI (Q94-Q106) ═══
{id:94,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is VLSI?",ans:"VLSI (Very Large Scale Integration) is the process of creating integrated circuits with <strong>thousands to billions of transistors</strong> on a single chip. Complexity levels: SSI (<100), MSI (100-1000), LSI (1000-100K), VLSI (100K-1M), ULSI (>1M). Modern processors have 50+ billion transistors. Feature sizes: currently 3-5 nm."},
{id:95,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is CMOS technology?",ans:"CMOS (Complementary MOS) uses paired <strong>N-channel and P-channel MOSFETs</strong>. When input is HIGH: NMOS ON, PMOS OFF. When LOW: PMOS ON, NMOS OFF. <strong>Zero static power</strong> (no DC path from VDD to GND in either state). Power consumption only during switching. Dominates all modern digital ICs."},
{id:96,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is Moore's Law?",ans:"<strong>Moore's Law:</strong> the number of transistors on a chip doubles approximately every 2 years. Observed by Gordon Moore in 1965. Has held true for decades, driving exponential growth in computing power. Currently approaching physical limits (atomic-scale transistors). Alternatives: 3D stacking, new materials, quantum computing."},
{id:97,topic:"vlsi",q:"Explain the CMOS inverter.",ans:"A CMOS inverter has PMOS (top, connected to VDD) and NMOS (bottom, connected to GND) with gates connected together as input. <strong>Input HIGH:</strong> NMOS ON → output LOW. <strong>Input LOW:</strong> PMOS ON → output HIGH. Switching threshold at VDD/2. No static power. Dynamic power = C×VDD²×f."},
{id:98,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is propagation delay in VLSI?",ans:"Propagation delay (tp) is the time from input change to output change, measured at 50% transition points. <strong>tp = (tpHL + tpLH)/2</strong>. Depends on: transistor size (W/L ratio), load capacitance, supply voltage. Smaller transistors → faster switching but more leakage. Critical for clock speed determination."},
{id:99,topic:"vlsi",q:"What are the VLSI design methodologies?",ans:"<strong>1. Full custom:</strong> Every transistor hand-designed. Best performance but slowest design time. For processors.\n<strong>2. Standard cell:</strong> Pre-designed cells placed and routed automatically. Balance of performance and design speed.\n<strong>3. Gate array/Sea of gates:</strong> Pre-fabricated transistors, only metal routing customized.\n<strong>4. FPGA:</strong> Programmed by user after fabrication. Fastest time-to-market."},
{id:100,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is the VLSI design flow?",ans:"<strong>1. Specification</strong> → <strong>2. Architecture design</strong> → <strong>3. RTL coding</strong> (Verilog/VHDL) → <strong>4. Functional simulation</strong> → <strong>5. Synthesis</strong> (RTL to gates) → <strong>6. Place and Route</strong> → <strong>7. Timing analysis</strong> (STA) → <strong>8. Physical verification</strong> (DRC, LVS) → <strong>9. Fabrication</strong> → <strong>10. Testing</strong>."},
{id:101,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is Verilog HDL?",ans:"Verilog is a <strong>Hardware Description Language</strong> used to model digital systems. Describes circuit behavior (behavioral) or structure (structural). Used for: RTL design, simulation, and synthesis. Supports modules, always blocks, assign statements. Alternative: VHDL (more verbose, popular in Europe and defense). SystemVerilog extends Verilog for verification."},
{id:102,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is static timing analysis (STA)?",ans:"STA verifies that all timing constraints are met <strong>without simulation</strong>. Checks: setup time (data stable before clock edge), hold time (data stable after clock edge), clock-to-q delay, propagation delay. <strong>Critical path:</strong> longest delay path that limits the maximum clock frequency. Slack = Required time − Arrival time (must be ≥ 0)."},
{id:103,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is power dissipation in CMOS?",ans:"<strong>Dynamic power:</strong> Pdyn = α×C×VDD²×f (α = activity factor, C = capacitance, f = frequency). Dominates at high speed.\n<strong>Static power:</strong> Pstatic = Ileak × VDD (leakage current). Dominates at nanometer scales.\n<strong>Short-circuit power:</strong> during switching, both transistors briefly ON.\nTotal = Dynamic + Static + Short-circuit."},
{id:104,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is DRC and LVS in VLSI?",ans:"<strong>DRC (Design Rule Check):</strong> verifies that the layout meets fabrication rules — minimum width, spacing, overlap requirements. <strong>LVS (Layout vs Schematic):</strong> verifies that the physical layout matches the intended circuit schematic. Both are essential verification steps before sending design for fabrication (tape-out)."},
{id:105,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is clock tree synthesis (CTS)?",ans:"CTS distributes the clock signal to all flip-flops with <strong>minimum skew</strong> (difference in arrival times). Uses balanced tree structures (H-tree, fishbone) with buffers. <strong>Clock skew</strong> causes setup and hold violations. CTS also considers clock jitter (random variation) and latency. Critical for high-speed designs."},
{id:106,topic:"vlsi",q:"What is an ASIC vs FPGA?",ans:"<strong>ASIC:</strong> Application-Specific IC — custom-designed for one function. Higher performance, lower power, lower cost at volume. Long design time, high NRE (Non-Recurring Engineering) cost.\n<strong>FPGA:</strong> Field-Programmable — can be reconfigured. Faster time-to-market, flexible. Higher unit cost, higher power, lower performance. Used for prototyping and low-volume."},

// ═══ Electronics 1 (Q107-Q119) ═══
{id:107,topic:"elec1",q:"What is the energy band theory?",ans:"In solids, atomic energy levels merge into <strong>bands</strong>: Valence band (filled with electrons), Conduction band (available for conduction), and Forbidden gap (energy band gap Eg). <strong>Conductors:</strong> overlapping bands (Eg=0). <strong>Semiconductors:</strong> small Eg (0.5-3 eV). <strong>Insulators:</strong> large Eg (>3 eV). Band theory explains electrical conductivity."},
{id:108,topic:"elec1",q:"Explain PN junction diode characteristics.",ans:"<strong>Forward bias:</strong> current increases exponentially after ~0.7V (Si). I = Is(e^(V/nVT) − 1). <strong>Reverse bias:</strong> very small leakage current (Is ~ nA). At breakdown voltage: large reverse current (avalanche or Zener). <strong>I-V characteristic</strong> is highly nonlinear. Used for rectification, switching, protection."},
{id:109,topic:"elec1",q:"What is the h-parameter model of a BJT?",ans:"h-parameters characterize the BJT as a two-port: <strong>hie</strong> (input impedance, ~1-5kΩ), <strong>hre</strong> (reverse voltage ratio, ~10⁻⁴), <strong>hfe</strong> (forward current gain β, 50-300), <strong>hoe</strong> (output admittance, ~10⁻⁵ S). CE configuration: Av ≈ −hfe×RL/hie. These parameters are frequency and bias dependent."},
{id:110,topic:"elec1",q:"What is the load line analysis?",ans:"The DC load line represents all possible operating points on the transistor's I-V characteristics. Equation: <strong>VCE = VCC − IC(RC + RE)</strong>. Intersection with transistor curves gives the Q-point. AC load line considers AC impedances (parallel combination of RC, RL). Q-point should be in the middle for maximum signal swing."},
{id:111,topic:"elec1",q:"What is the small-signal model of a BJT?",ans:"The small-signal (AC) model replaces the BJT with linear elements for AC analysis. <strong>Hybrid-π model:</strong> rπ = VT/IB (input resistance), gm = IC/VT (transconductance), ro = VA/IC (output resistance). Voltage gain: Av = −gmRC (CE). Used when signal amplitude is small enough for linear approximation."},
{id:112,topic:"elec1",q:"What is the frequency response of a CE amplifier?",ans:"<strong>Low-frequency cutoff:</strong> due to coupling and bypass capacitors. fL = 1/(2πR₁C₁). <strong>Mid-band:</strong> flat gain (all capacitors are short circuits, internal capacitances are open). <strong>High-frequency cutoff:</strong> due to internal device capacitances (Cπ, Cμ — Miller effect). fH = 1/(2πRin×Cin_total). Bandwidth = fH − fL."},
{id:113,topic:"elec1",q:"What is a current mirror?",ans:"A current mirror copies a reference current to another branch. Two matched transistors: Q1 (diode-connected) sets the reference, Q2 mirrors it. <strong>Iout = Iref × (W/L)₂/(W/L)₁</strong>. Used in IC biasing, active loads, and DACs. Advantages: simple, accurate, temperature-compensated (matched transistors). Wilson and cascode mirrors improve accuracy."},
{id:114,topic:"elec1",q:"What is the Early voltage in a BJT?",ans:"Early voltage (VA) characterizes the output conductance in the active region. IC has a slight slope vs VCE (not perfectly horizontal). <strong>VA = extrapolated VCE intercept</strong> on the IC axis. Typically 50-200V. Output resistance ro = VA/IC. Higher VA = more ideal (flatter IC). Affects amplifier gain: Av(max) = gmro = VA/VT."},
{id:115,topic:"elec1",q:"What is the β (current gain) variation issue?",ans:"β varies significantly with: temperature (increases ~1%/°C), IC (peaks at mid-range), manufacturing (can vary 3:1 between devices of same type). <strong>Good design should not depend on exact β value</strong>. Voltage divider bias provides Q-point stability. Current mirrors use matched transistors. Feedback reduces β sensitivity."},
{id:116,topic:"elec1",q:"What are the different types of biasing circuits?",ans:"<strong>1. Fixed bias:</strong> RB from VCC to base. Simple but very β-sensitive.\n<strong>2. Collector feedback:</strong> RB from collector to base. Better stability.\n<strong>3. Voltage divider:</strong> R₁-R₂ divider + RE. Most stable. Standard choice.\n<strong>4. Emitter bias:</strong> Two supply (+VCC, −VEE). Very stable. Used in differential pairs.\nAll aim to stabilize Q-point against temperature and β variation."},
{id:117,topic:"elec1",q:"What is a Zener regulator circuit?",ans:"A Zener diode in reverse bias maintains a constant voltage VZ across the load. Series resistor Rs limits current: <strong>Rs = (Vin − VZ)/IZ</strong>. Load voltage = VZ (constant). Regulation: IZ adjusts as Vin or IL change. Limitations: low efficiency for large Vin/VZ ratio, limited current capability. Used for simple voltage references."},
{id:118,topic:"elec1",q:"What is the concept of transconductance (gm)?",ans:"Transconductance is the ratio of output current change to input voltage change: <strong>gm = ΔIC/ΔVBE = IC/VT</strong> (for BJT), gm = 2ID/(VGS−Vth) (for MOSFET). VT ≈ 26mV at room temperature. gm determines the voltage gain: Av = −gm×RL. Higher gm = higher gain. BJTs have higher gm than FETs at same bias current."},
{id:119,topic:"elec1",q:"What are coupling and bypass capacitors?",ans:"<strong>Coupling capacitors:</strong> connect stages while blocking DC. Allow AC signal to pass between amplifier stages without disturbing bias points. Size: must have low reactance at signal frequency.\n<strong>Bypass capacitors:</strong> provide AC ground for a node (e.g., emitter bypass CE). Short-circuits AC signal around a resistor. Both set the low-frequency cutoff."},

// ═══ Electronics 2 (Q120-Q132) ═══
{id:120,topic:"elec2",q:"What is an oscillator?",ans:"An oscillator generates a periodic waveform (sine, square, triangle) without any external input signal. Uses <strong>positive feedback</strong> with a frequency-selective network. Barkhausen criterion: loop gain |Aβ| = 1 and phase shift = 0°/360°. Types: RC (Wien bridge, phase shift), LC (Colpitts, Hartley), Crystal (quartz). Self-starting: gain initially > 1, then stabilizes."},
{id:121,topic:"elec2",q:"What is a Wien bridge oscillator?",ans:"The Wien bridge oscillator uses an <strong>RC lead-lag network</strong> (R-C series + R-C parallel) for frequency selection and a non-inverting amplifier with gain = 3. <strong>f₀ = 1/(2πRC)</strong>. At f₀, the RC network provides 0° phase shift and 1/3 attenuation. Gain of 3 × 1/3 = 1 loop gain. Produces clean sine wave. Gain stabilized by non-linear feedback (lamp, diode)."},
{id:122,topic:"elec2",q:"Explain Class A, B, AB amplifier operation.",ans:"<strong>Class A:</strong> Transistor conducts for full 360° cycle. Lowest distortion, highest fidelity. Efficiency ~25% (transformer-coupled: ~50%). Always ON.\n<strong>Class B:</strong> Conducts for 180° (half cycle). Push-pull configuration. Efficiency ~78.5%. Crossover distortion.\n<strong>Class AB:</strong> Conducts slightly more than 180°. Small bias eliminates crossover distortion. Efficiency ~50-70%. Most common in audio."},
{id:123,topic:"elec2",q:"What is a regulated power supply?",ans:"A regulated power supply provides a <strong>constant DC output</strong> despite input voltage and load changes. Block diagram: AC input → Transformer → Rectifier → Filter → Regulator → DC output. Regulator types: Zener (simple), Series pass (linear — 7805, LM317), Switching (buck/boost — high efficiency). Key specs: regulation, ripple, load/line regulation."},
{id:124,topic:"elec2",q:"What is a switching power supply?",ans:"A switching power supply uses a transistor as a high-frequency switch (50-1000 kHz) rather than a linear regulator. Types: <strong>Buck</strong> (step-down), <strong>Boost</strong> (step-up), <strong>Buck-Boost</strong>, <strong>Flyback</strong> (isolated). Efficiency: 80-95%. Much lighter than linear (smaller transformer at high frequency). Used in computers, phone chargers, EVs."},
{id:125,topic:"elec2",q:"What is a PLL (Phase-Locked Loop)?",ans:"A PLL is a control system that generates an output signal whose phase is locked to the input signal. Components: <strong>Phase detector</strong> (compares input/output phase), <strong>Loop filter</strong> (LPF), <strong>VCO</strong> (Voltage-Controlled Oscillator). Applications: FM demodulation, frequency synthesis, clock recovery, motor speed control, frequency multiplication."},
{id:126,topic:"elec2",q:"What is a voltage-controlled oscillator (VCO)?",ans:"A VCO generates a periodic signal whose frequency is controlled by an input voltage. <strong>f = f₀ + Kv × Vc</strong>, where Kv is the VCO gain (Hz/V). Used in PLLs, FM modulators, function generators. Types: LC-based (high frequency), RC-based (lower frequency), ring oscillator (IC implementation)."},
{id:127,topic:"elec2",q:"What is a sample-and-hold circuit?",ans:"A sample-and-hold (S/H) captures an analog signal and holds it constant during ADC conversion. <strong>Switch (MOSFET) + Hold capacitor + Buffer</strong>. In sample mode: switch ON, capacitor tracks input. In hold mode: switch OFF, capacitor holds the sampled value. Essential for accurate ADC conversion. Acquisition time and droop rate are key specs."},
{id:128,topic:"elec2",q:"What is a Schmitt trigger?",ans:"A Schmitt trigger is a comparator with <strong>hysteresis</strong> (two different threshold voltages: UTP and LTP). Uses positive feedback. Input rising: switches at UTP. Input falling: switches at LTP. Hysteresis = UTP − LTP. Converts noisy/slow signals to clean digital signals. Prevents oscillation near threshold. Used in wave shaping and debouncing."},
{id:129,topic:"elec2",q:"What is an instrumentation amplifier?",ans:"An instrumentation amplifier is a precision differential amplifier with: <strong>very high input impedance</strong>, high CMRR (>100 dB), <strong>adjustable gain with single resistor</strong>. Uses three op-amps: two input buffers and one difference amplifier. Gain = 1 + 2R/Rgain. Used for sensors (strain gauges, thermocouples, biomedical signals)."},
{id:130,topic:"elec2",q:"What is an active rectifier?",ans:"An active (precision) rectifier uses op-amps with diodes to overcome the 0.7V forward drop limitation. The op-amp forces the diode to conduct at the correct zero-crossing. <strong>Can rectify millivolt signals accurately</strong>. Used in precision AC-to-DC converters, signal processing, and instrumentation where low-level signals need rectification."},
{id:131,topic:"elec2",q:"What is a log and antilog amplifier?",ans:"<strong>Log amplifier:</strong> output proportional to log of input. Uses diode/transistor in feedback of inverting op-amp. Vout = −VT × ln(Vin/IsR). Used for signal compression, dB measurement.\n<strong>Antilog (exponential) amplifier:</strong> output = antilog of input. Diode/transistor at input. Used for signal expansion. Together used in analog multipliers and dividers."},
{id:132,topic:"elec2",q:"What is a waveform generator IC?",ans:"ICs like <strong>ICL8038</strong> and <strong>XR2206</strong> generate simultaneous sine, square, and triangle waveforms. Frequency set by external R and C. Frequency range: 0.001 Hz to 300 kHz. Features: FM and AM capability, sweep generation, duty cycle control. Modern: DDS (Direct Digital Synthesis) chips like AD9833 for higher precision and wider range."},

// ═══ Electronics 3 (Q133-Q145) ═══
{id:133,topic:"elec3",q:"What is an ADC (Analog to Digital Converter)?",ans:"ADC converts analog voltage to digital code. <strong>Key parameters:</strong> Resolution (n bits → 2ⁿ levels), Sampling rate, SNR = 6.02n + 1.76 dB. <strong>Types:</strong> Flash (fastest, expensive), SAR (balanced — most common), Sigma-Delta (highest resolution, slow — audio/measurement), Pipeline (high-speed data acquisition)."},
{id:134,topic:"elec3",q:"What is a DAC (Digital to Analog Converter)?",ans:"DAC converts digital code to analog voltage. <strong>Types:</strong> Weighted resistor (simple but inaccurate for many bits), R-2R ladder (uses only two resistor values — most common), Current-steering (high-speed). Key specs: Resolution, Settling time, Linearity (INL, DNL), Glitch energy. Output: staircase waveform, needs reconstruction filter."},
{id:135,topic:"elec3",q:"What is a timer IC 555 in detail?",ans:"The 555 contains: <strong>3 × 5kΩ resistors</strong> (voltage divider → ⅓Vcc, ⅔Vcc), 2 comparators, SR flip-flop, discharge transistor, output driver. <strong>Monostable:</strong> T = 1.1RC. <strong>Astable:</strong> f = 1.44/((R₁+2R₂)C), duty > 50%. Can achieve 50% duty with diode modification. Supply: 4.5-16V. Output: ~200mA source/sink."},
{id:136,topic:"elec3",q:"What is a voltage regulator IC (78xx, LM317)?",ans:"<strong>78xx series:</strong> Fixed positive regulators. 7805=+5V, 7812=+12V, 7815=+15V. Dropout ~2V. Max current ~1A with heatsink. <strong>79xx:</strong> Negative regulators.\n<strong>LM317:</strong> Adjustable 1.25-37V. Vout = 1.25(1 + R₂/R₁). 1.5A max. Needs minimum load current. Thermal shutdown protection. Both are linear regulators."},
{id:137,topic:"elec3",q:"What is a data acquisition system?",ans:"A DAS captures real-world signals: <strong>Sensor → Signal conditioning → Multiplexer → S/H → ADC → Digital processor/storage</strong>. Signal conditioning: amplification, filtering, isolation, linearization. Multiplexer: selects one of many channels. Key specs: number of channels, sample rate, resolution, accuracy. Used in industrial monitoring and testing."},
{id:138,topic:"elec3",q:"What is a comparator?",ans:"A comparator compares two voltages and outputs HIGH or LOW. <strong>If V+ > V−: output HIGH. If V+ < V−: output LOW.</strong> Similar to an op-amp in open-loop, but optimized for speed (fast slew rate, no compensation). Dedicated ICs: LM339, LM393. For noise immunity, add hysteresis (Schmitt trigger). Used in ADCs, zero-crossing detectors, level sensors."},
{id:139,topic:"elec3",q:"What is PWM (Pulse Width Modulation)?",ans:"PWM varies the duty cycle of a pulse train to control average power. <strong>Average voltage = D × Vpeak</strong> (D = duty cycle). Methods: Compare triangle wave with reference (analog), Timer counter (digital). Applications: motor speed control, LED dimming, power converters (buck, boost), audio Class D amplifiers, servo control."},
{id:140,topic:"elec3",q:"What is a charge pump?",ans:"A charge pump is a DC-DC converter using <strong>switched capacitors</strong> to multiply or invert voltage. No inductor needed (unlike buck/boost). Simple, low noise, small. Types: voltage doubler (2×Vin), voltage inverter (−Vin). Common IC: ICL7660 (inverts voltage). Limited current capability (~100mA). Used for op-amp negative supply in single-supply systems."},
{id:141,topic:"elec3",q:"What is an analog multiplexer?",ans:"An analog multiplexer (AMUX) routes one of several analog signals to a single output. Controlled by digital select lines. Uses MOSFET switches (bilateral — passes both directions). <strong>CD4051:</strong> 8-channel AMUX. Key specs: ON resistance (50-200Ω), switching time, crosstalk, bandwidth. Used in data acquisition, audio routing, test equipment."},
{id:142,topic:"elec3",q:"What is a phase-shift oscillator?",ans:"A phase-shift oscillator uses three RC stages, each providing 60° phase shift (total 180°), with an inverting amplifier (+180°) for total 360°. <strong>f = 1/(2π√6RC)</strong>. Gain must be ≥ 29 for oscillation. Simple design. Produces reasonable sine wave but limited frequency range. Used for audio tone generation."},
{id:143,topic:"elec3",q:"What is an active load in amplifier design?",ans:"An active load replaces a passive resistor with a <strong>transistor (current mirror)</strong> as the collector/drain load. Advantages: very high effective resistance (rd) → very high voltage gain (Av = −gm × rd). Saves chip area (transistor < large resistor on IC). All modern op-amps and analog ICs use active loads. Key to high-gain amplifier design."},
{id:144,topic:"elec3",q:"What is a bootstrap circuit?",ans:"Bootstrap uses positive feedback to increase effective impedance. A capacitor couples the output back to the input bias point, making the voltage across the bias resistor constant → <strong>effective input impedance increases dramatically</strong>. Used in source/emitter followers to increase input impedance. The 'bootstrapped' resistor appears much larger than its actual value."},
{id:145,topic:"elec3",q:"What is noise in electronic circuits?",ans:"Electronic noise is unwanted random signal that degrades SNR. <strong>Types:</strong> Thermal noise (Johnson, kTBR — all resistors), Shot noise (2qIdcB — junction devices), Flicker (1/f — low frequency, semiconductor surfaces), Burst (popcorn), Avalanche. <strong>Noise figure:</strong> NF = SNRin/SNRout (dB). Low-noise design: minimize R, choose low-noise devices, use bandlimiting."},

// ═══ Signal & System (Q146-Q159) ═══
{id:146,topic:"sns",q:"What is a signal?",ans:"A signal is a function that conveys information about a physical phenomenon. <strong>Continuous-time (CT):</strong> defined for all t (analog). <strong>Discrete-time (DT):</strong> defined only at integer time indices n (digital). Types: deterministic (predictable) vs random (statistical). Energy signal: finite energy. Power signal: finite average power. Described mathematically as x(t) or x[n]."},
{id:147,topic:"sns",q:"What is a system?",ans:"A system processes an input signal to produce an output signal: <strong>y(t) = T{x(t)}</strong>. Properties: <strong>Linear</strong> (superposition holds), <strong>Time-invariant</strong> (behavior doesn't change with time), <strong>Causal</strong> (output depends only on present/past input), <strong>Stable</strong> (bounded input → bounded output — BIBO). LTI systems are the most commonly analyzed."},
{id:148,topic:"sns",q:"What is convolution?",ans:"Convolution finds the output of an LTI system: <strong>y(t) = x(t) * h(t) = ∫x(τ)h(t−τ)dτ</strong>, where h(t) is the impulse response. Properties: commutative, associative, distributive. In frequency domain: Y(ω) = X(ω)H(ω) (multiplication). This is the most fundamental operation for LTI system analysis."},
{id:149,topic:"sns",q:"What is the Fourier Transform?",ans:"The Fourier Transform decomposes a signal into its frequency components: <strong>X(ω) = ∫x(t)e^(−jωt)dt</strong>. Inverse: x(t) = (1/2π)∫X(ω)e^(jωt)dω. Converts time-domain to frequency-domain. Properties: linearity, time shift → phase shift, convolution ↔ multiplication. Exists for signals with finite energy."},
{id:150,topic:"sns",q:"What is the Laplace Transform?",ans:"The Laplace Transform generalizes the Fourier Transform: <strong>X(s) = ∫x(t)e^(−st)dt</strong>, s = σ+jω. Handles a wider class of signals (growing exponentials). The Region of Convergence (ROC) must be specified. Transfer function H(s) = Y(s)/X(s). Poles and zeros determine system behavior. Essential for control systems and circuit analysis."},
{id:151,topic:"sns",q:"What is the Z-Transform?",ans:"The Z-Transform is the discrete-time equivalent of the Laplace Transform: <strong>X(z) = Σx[n]z^(−n)</strong>. Transfer function H(z) = Y(z)/X(z). z = e^(sT). Unit circle in z-plane corresponds to jω axis in s-plane. Used in digital signal processing, digital filter design, and discrete-time control systems. ROC determines stability and causality."},
{id:152,topic:"sns",q:"What is the sampling theorem?",ans:"The sampling theorem states: a bandlimited signal with maximum frequency fmax can be perfectly reconstructed from its samples if the sampling rate <strong>fs ≥ 2fmax</strong> (Nyquist rate). Sampling creates spectral copies at multiples of fs. If fs < 2fmax: spectral overlap → <strong>aliasing</strong> (frequency confusion). Anti-aliasing filter needed before sampling."},
{id:153,topic:"sns",q:"What is a causal system?",ans:"A causal system's output depends only on present and past inputs: <strong>y(t) depends only on x(τ) for τ ≤ t</strong>. The impulse response h(t) = 0 for t < 0. All real-time physical systems are causal. In the s-domain: the ROC of a causal system is to the right of the rightmost pole. Non-causal systems exist only in offline processing."},
{id:154,topic:"sns",q:"What is BIBO stability?",ans:"BIBO (Bounded-Input Bounded-Output) stability: if every bounded input produces a bounded output. Condition: <strong>∫|h(t)|dt < ∞</strong> (impulse response is absolutely integrable). In s-domain: all poles must be in the left half plane (Re(s) < 0). In z-domain: all poles must be inside the unit circle (|z| < 1)."},
{id:155,topic:"sns",q:"What are energy and power signals?",ans:"<strong>Energy signal:</strong> finite total energy E = ∫|x(t)|²dt < ∞, zero average power. Example: pulse, decaying exponential.\n<strong>Power signal:</strong> infinite energy, finite average power P = lim(T→∞) (1/2T)∫|x(t)|²dt. Example: sinusoid, periodic signals.\nA signal cannot be both. Some are neither (e.g., ramp)."},
{id:156,topic:"sns",q:"What is the impulse response of a system?",ans:"The impulse response h(t) is the output when the input is a unit impulse δ(t). It completely characterizes an LTI system: <strong>y(t) = x(t) * h(t)</strong>. In frequency domain: H(ω) = FT{h(t)} is the frequency response. Stable system: h(t) decays to zero. Causal system: h(t) = 0 for t < 0."},
{id:157,topic:"sns",q:"What are even and odd signals?",ans:"<strong>Even signal:</strong> x(−t) = x(t). Symmetric about t=0. Example: cos(t), |t|.\n<strong>Odd signal:</strong> x(−t) = −x(t). Anti-symmetric. x(0) = 0. Example: sin(t), t.\nAny signal can be decomposed: x(t) = xe(t) + xo(t), where xe = [x(t)+x(−t)]/2 and xo = [x(t)−x(−t)]/2."},
{id:158,topic:"sns",q:"What is the DFT (Discrete Fourier Transform)?",ans:"DFT converts N samples of a discrete signal to N frequency components: <strong>X[k] = Σx[n]e^(−j2πkn/N)</strong>. Inverse: x[n] = (1/N)Σx[k]e^(j2πkn/N). Computationally: O(N²) operations. <strong>FFT</strong> (Fast Fourier Transform) reduces to O(N log₂N). Used in spectrum analysis, filtering, image processing, audio processing."},
{id:159,topic:"sns",q:"What is the difference between FIR and IIR filters?",ans:"<strong>FIR (Finite Impulse Response):</strong> h[n] has finite length. Always stable. Linear phase possible. No feedback. Higher order needed for sharp cutoff.\n<strong>IIR (Infinite Impulse Response):</strong> h[n] is infinite (recursive, has feedback). Can be unstable. Non-linear phase. Lower order for same specifications. Designed from analog prototypes (Butterworth, Chebyshev)."},

// ═══ Electrical Measurement (Q160-Q172) ═══
{id:160,topic:"eem",q:"What are the types of errors in measurement?",ans:"<strong>1. Systematic errors:</strong> Instrument errors (calibration, zero, loading), Environmental (temperature, humidity), Observational (parallax). Predictable and correctable.\n<strong>2. Random errors:</strong> Unpredictable variations. Reduced by averaging multiple readings. Follow Gaussian distribution.\n<strong>3. Gross errors:</strong> Human mistakes — misreading, wrong connection, recording errors. Avoided by care and repeated readings."},
{id:161,topic:"eem",q:"What is the PMMC (Permanent Magnet Moving Coil) instrument?",ans:"PMMC uses a coil rotating in a permanent magnetic field. Torque ∝ current. <strong>Measures DC only</strong> (for AC, needs rectifier). Advantages: linear scale, high accuracy (0.1%), high sensitivity. Disadvantages: DC only, delicate, expensive. Used in high-quality ammeters, voltmeters, and galvanometers. Sensitivity in Ω/V."},
{id:162,topic:"eem",q:"What is a moving iron instrument?",ans:"Moving iron instrument uses attraction or repulsion of iron vanes by a current-carrying coil. Works on <strong>both AC and DC</strong> (reads RMS). Advantages: simple, rugged, cheap. Disadvantages: non-linear scale, lower accuracy (1-2%), affected by hysteresis and stray fields. Used for panel meters, industrial measurements."},
{id:163,topic:"eem",q:"What is a dynamometer type wattmeter?",ans:"Dynamometer wattmeter has <strong>two coils:</strong> Fixed current coil (in series — carries load current) and Moving pressure coil (in parallel — proportional to voltage). Deflection ∝ VI cosφ = <strong>real power</strong>. Works on AC and DC. Most accurate power measurement method. Used as laboratory standard."},
{id:164,topic:"eem",q:"What is a CT (Current Transformer)?",ans:"CT steps down high current to measurable level. Primary: 1 or few turns (in series with line). Secondary: many turns (connected to ammeter/relay). <strong>Is = Ip × Np/Ns</strong>. Standard secondary: 5A or 1A. <strong>NEVER open the secondary</strong> — causes dangerously high voltage. Accuracy classes: 0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 1.0 (for metering); 5P, 10P (for protection)."},
{id:165,topic:"eem",q:"What is the Kelvin double bridge?",ans:"The Kelvin double bridge measures <strong>very low resistances</strong> (< 1Ω) accurately, overcoming contact and lead resistance errors of the standard Wheatstone bridge. It uses four arms plus two additional ratio arms to eliminate the effect of lead and contact resistance. Accuracy: 0.01%. Used for measuring shunt resistors, cable resistance."},
{id:166,topic:"eem",q:"What is a potentiometer in measurement?",ans:"A measurement potentiometer compares an unknown voltage against a standard cell using <strong>null deflection method</strong>. Draws zero current from the source at balance → no loading error. Very high accuracy (0.01%). Used for calibrating voltmeters, measuring EMF of cells, and standardizing instruments. Types: Crompton, Kelvin-Varley."},
{id:167,topic:"eem",q:"What is a digital storage oscilloscope (DSO)?",ans:"A DSO digitizes the input signal and stores it in memory. <strong>Components:</strong> Attenuator → ADC → Memory → Display processor → Screen. Advantages over analog: can capture single events, pre-trigger viewing, waveform storage/analysis, automated measurements, math functions (FFT). Key specs: bandwidth, sample rate, record length, resolution."},
{id:168,topic:"eem",q:"What is the AC bridge?",ans:"AC bridges measure impedance (R, L, C) at a specific frequency using the null balance method. Types: <strong>Maxwell bridge</strong> (inductance), <strong>Wien bridge</strong> (frequency, capacitance), <strong>Schering bridge</strong> (capacitance, dissipation factor), <strong>Anderson bridge</strong> (inductance). At balance, unknown impedance is calculated from known components."},
{id:169,topic:"eem",q:"What is the Maxwell bridge?",ans:"Maxwell bridge measures <strong>unknown inductance L and its resistance R</strong>. Uses a standard capacitor as reference (more stable than standard inductor). Balance conditions: Lx = R₂R₃C₁ and Rx = R₂R₃/R₁. Advantages: simple balance equations, uses standard capacitor. Suitable for medium Q inductors (1 < Q < 10)."},
{id:170,topic:"eem",q:"What is the difference between accuracy and precision in measurements?",ans:"<strong>Accuracy:</strong> closeness of measurement to the true (accepted) value. Affected by systematic errors.\n<strong>Precision:</strong> closeness of repeated measurements to each other (repeatability/reproducibility). Affected by random errors.\nA measurement can be precise but inaccurate (consistent bias) or accurate but imprecise (scattered around true value)."},
{id:171,topic:"eem",q:"What is a thermocouple and how does it work?",ans:"A thermocouple generates voltage proportional to temperature difference between two junctions of dissimilar metals (<strong>Seebeck effect</strong>). Types: K (Chromel-Alumel, −200 to 1260°C — most common), J (Iron-Constantan), T (Copper-Constantan), S/R (Platinum — high temp). Requires cold junction compensation. Self-powered, fast response, wide range."},
{id:172,topic:"eem",q:"What is the concept of virtual instrumentation?",ans:"Virtual instrumentation uses <strong>software + general-purpose hardware</strong> (DAQ cards, PCs) to replace dedicated instruments. <strong>LabVIEW</strong> is the most popular platform. Advantages: flexible, customizable, cost-effective, can combine multiple instrument functions. The instrument is defined by software, not hardware. Standard interface: GPIB, USB, LAN."},

// ═══ Power Plant Engineering (Q173-Q186) ═══
{id:173,topic:"ppe",q:"What are the types of power plants?",ans:"<strong>1. Thermal:</strong> Coal, gas, oil, nuclear (steam turbine). ~60% of global capacity.\n<strong>2. Hydroelectric:</strong> Potential energy of water → turbine → generator. Clean, renewable.\n<strong>3. Nuclear:</strong> Fission of U-235/Pu-239. High energy density, low emissions.\n<strong>4. Renewable:</strong> Solar PV, Wind, Biomass, Geothermal, Tidal.\n<strong>5. Gas turbine:</strong> Open cycle, combined cycle (CCGT — most efficient fossil, ~60%)."},
{id:174,topic:"ppe",q:"What is the Rankine cycle?",ans:"The Rankine cycle is the thermodynamic cycle for steam power plants. <strong>4 processes:</strong> 1. Boiler (heat addition at constant pressure — water to steam). 2. Turbine (isentropic expansion — steam does work). 3. Condenser (heat rejection at constant pressure — steam to water). 4. Feed pump (isentropic compression — water pressurized). Efficiency: ~33-42%."},
{id:175,topic:"ppe",q:"What is the efficiency of a thermal power plant?",ans:"Overall efficiency = Generator output / Heat input from fuel. <strong>Typical: 33-42%</strong>. Losses: stack gas (25-35%), condenser (40-50%), radiation, auxiliary power. Improving efficiency: reheat cycle, regenerative cycle (feed water heaters), supercritical/ultra-supercritical steam conditions, combined cycle (gas + steam). Every 1% improvement saves significant fuel."},
{id:176,topic:"ppe",q:"What is a combined cycle power plant (CCGT)?",ans:"CCGT combines gas turbine (Brayton cycle) and steam turbine (Rankine cycle). Gas turbine exhaust (500-600°C) → <strong>Heat Recovery Steam Generator (HRSG)</strong> → Steam turbine. Overall efficiency: <strong>55-62%</strong> (vs ~35% for simple cycle). Fast startup, lower emissions. Most efficient fossil fuel technology. Natural gas fuel."},
{id:177,topic:"ppe",q:"What is the load duration curve?",ans:"A load duration curve plots load (MW) vs percentage of time the load is exceeded, arranged in descending order. Shows <strong>base load</strong> (continuous, bottom), <strong>intermediate load</strong> (daily cycling), and <strong>peak load</strong> (short duration, top). Used for generation planning: base load → coal/nuclear, peak → gas turbine/hydro. Area under curve = total energy."},
{id:178,topic:"ppe",q:"What is capacity factor and plant factor?",ans:"<strong>Capacity factor</strong> = Actual energy generated / Maximum possible energy = E_actual/(P_rated × 8760 hours). Typical: Nuclear ~90%, Coal ~60-80%, Wind ~25-35%, Solar ~15-25%. <strong>Plant factor</strong> ≈ capacity factor for thermal plants. Higher capacity factor = better utilization of investment."},
{id:179,topic:"ppe",q:"What is a nuclear power plant?",ans:"Nuclear power uses <strong>fission</strong> of U-235 (or Pu-239) to generate heat → steam → turbine → generator. Components: Reactor core (fuel rods + control rods + moderator), Coolant (water, heavy water, gas), Steam generator, Containment structure. Types: PWR (most common), BWR, PHWR (CANDU), Fast breeder. No CO₂ emissions but radioactive waste issue."},
{id:180,topic:"ppe",q:"What is a hydroelectric power plant?",ans:"Hydroelectric converts <strong>potential energy of water</strong> to electricity. Power P = ρgQH × η, where Q = flow rate, H = head (height), η = efficiency (~85-90%). Types: Storage (dam), Run-of-river (minimal storage), Pumped storage (energy storage). Advantages: clean, renewable, long life (50-100 years), fast response. Disadvantage: site-specific, environmental impact."},
{id:181,topic:"ppe",q:"What is the heat rate of a power plant?",ans:"Heat rate = <strong>Heat input (kJ) / Electrical output (kWh)</strong>. Lower heat rate = higher efficiency. Efficiency = 3600/Heat rate. Typical: Coal plant: 10,000 kJ/kWh (36% efficient). CCGT: 6,000 kJ/kWh (60% efficient). Heat rate is the primary measure of a power plant's thermal efficiency."},
{id:182,topic:"ppe",q:"What is a cooling tower?",ans:"A cooling tower rejects heat from the condenser cooling water to the atmosphere. <strong>Types:</strong> Natural draft (large hyperbolic tower — uses buoyancy), Mechanical draft (fans — induced or forced). Wet cooling towers evaporate water for cooling. Dry cooling towers use air (no water consumption). Hybrid types exist. Large power plants evaporate millions of liters/day."},
{id:183,topic:"ppe",q:"What is the tariff structure for electricity?",ans:"<strong>Flat rate:</strong> Fixed price per kWh (simple but doesn't encourage conservation).\n<strong>Two-part tariff:</strong> Fixed charge (demand, kW) + Energy charge (kWh).\n<strong>Time-of-use (ToU):</strong> Different rates for peak, off-peak, shoulder periods.\n<strong>Maximum demand tariff:</strong> Based on highest demand in billing period.\n<strong>Real-time pricing:</strong> Price varies hourly based on supply/demand."},
{id:184,topic:"ppe",q:"What is cogeneration (CHP)?",ans:"Cogeneration (Combined Heat and Power) simultaneously produces <strong>electricity and useful thermal energy</strong> from the same fuel source. Overall efficiency: 70-90% (vs 35-40% for electricity alone). Waste heat used for: heating, cooling (absorption chiller), industrial processes. Types: Topping cycle (electricity first), Bottoming cycle (heat first)."},
{id:185,topic:"ppe",q:"What is the environmental impact of power plants?",ans:"<strong>Thermal (fossil):</strong> CO₂ (climate change), SOx (acid rain), NOx (smog), particulates, thermal pollution of water, ash disposal.\n<strong>Nuclear:</strong> Radioactive waste, accident risk, thermal pollution.\n<strong>Hydro:</strong> Ecosystem disruption, displacement, sedimentation.\n<strong>Wind:</strong> Bird strikes, noise, visual impact.\n<strong>Solar:</strong> Land use, manufacturing waste. All have environmental tradeoffs."},
{id:186,topic:"ppe",q:"What is a gas turbine power plant?",ans:"Gas turbine uses the <strong>Brayton cycle</strong>: Air compression → Combustion (with natural gas/diesel) → Expansion through turbine → Exhaust. Advantages: fast startup (minutes), compact, low capital cost, low water usage. Disadvantages: lower efficiency (~35% simple cycle), high fuel cost. Combined with steam turbine (CCGT) for 55-62% efficiency."},

// ═══ Control System (Q187-Q199) ═══
{id:187,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is a control system?",ans:"A control system manages, commands, or regulates the behavior of a system. <strong>Open-loop:</strong> output does not affect input (e.g., toaster, washing machine timer). <strong>Closed-loop (feedback):</strong> output is measured and compared with desired input; error drives the controller (e.g., thermostat, cruise control, PID controller). Feedback improves accuracy and disturbance rejection."},
{id:188,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is a transfer function?",ans:"Transfer function G(s) = Output(s)/Input(s) = Y(s)/X(s) for zero initial conditions. Describes the input-output relationship of an LTI system. Contains poles (stability, natural response) and zeros (response shape). <strong>Characteristic equation:</strong> denominator = 0, determines system stability and transient behavior."},
{id:189,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is the Routh-Hurwitz stability criterion?",ans:"Routh-Hurwitz determines system stability from the characteristic polynomial <strong>without finding actual pole locations</strong>. Construct the Routh array from polynomial coefficients. <strong>Stability condition:</strong> all elements in the first column must be positive (no sign changes). Number of sign changes = number of roots in the right half plane (RHP)."},
{id:190,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is the root locus?",ans:"Root locus plots the paths of closed-loop poles as a parameter (usually gain K) varies from 0 to ∞. <strong>Rules:</strong> Starts at open-loop poles (K=0), ends at zeros (K→∞), on real axis to the left of odd number of poles+zeros. Shows how stability changes with gain. Breakaway/break-in points, angles of departure/arrival help sketch the locus."},
{id:191,topic:"ctrl",q:"What are Bode plots in control systems?",ans:"Bode plots show the frequency response: <strong>Magnitude (|G(jω)| in dB) and Phase (∠G(jω) in degrees) vs log frequency</strong>. Used for: stability analysis (gain margin, phase margin), controller design (lead, lag compensation). Asymptotic approximations simplify drawing. <strong>Gain margin:</strong> gain at phase crossover. <strong>Phase margin:</strong> phase at gain crossover."},
{id:192,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is the Nyquist stability criterion?",ans:"The Nyquist plot maps G(jω)H(jω) as ω goes from −∞ to +∞ in the complex plane. <strong>Stability:</strong> the number of clockwise encirclements of the critical point (−1,0) = Z = N + P, where P = open-loop RHP poles, Z = closed-loop RHP poles. For stability: Z = 0 → N = −P. More general than Routh-Hurwitz for systems with time delay."},
{id:193,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is a PID controller?",ans:"PID = Proportional + Integral + Derivative controller. <strong>P:</strong> reduces error proportionally (Kp×e). <strong>I:</strong> eliminates steady-state error by integrating (Ki∫e dt). <strong>D:</strong> anticipates error by differentiating (Kd×de/dt). G(s) = Kp + Ki/s + Kd×s. Most widely used industrial controller. Tuning methods: Ziegler-Nichols, trial and error, auto-tune."},
{id:194,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is steady-state error?",ans:"Steady-state error (ess) is the difference between input and output as t→∞. Depends on <strong>system type</strong> (number of integrators in the loop). Type 0: finite ess for step input. Type 1: zero ess for step, finite for ramp. Type 2: zero for step and ramp, finite for parabolic. Error constants: Kp (position), Kv (velocity), Ka (acceleration)."},
{id:195,topic:"ctrl",q:"What are gain margin and phase margin?",ans:"<strong>Gain margin:</strong> how much gain can be increased before instability. Measured at phase crossover frequency (where phase = −180°). GM = 1/|G(jωpc)|. <strong>Phase margin:</strong> how much additional phase lag can be tolerated. Measured at gain crossover frequency (where |G(jω)| = 1 = 0 dB). PM = 180° + ∠G(jωgc). Both must be positive for stability."},
{id:196,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is the state-space representation?",ans:"State-space models a system using first-order differential equations: <strong>ẋ = Ax + Bu</strong> (state equation), <strong>y = Cx + Du</strong> (output equation). x = state vector, u = input, y = output. A, B, C, D are matrices. Advantages: handles MIMO systems, nonlinear systems, time-varying systems. Relationship: G(s) = C(sI−A)⁻¹B + D."},
{id:197,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is controllability and observability?",ans:"<strong>Controllability:</strong> can every state be driven to any desired value using the input? Test: rank of [B, AB, A²B, ..., Aⁿ⁻¹B] = n.\n<strong>Observability:</strong> can every state be determined from output measurements? Test: rank of [C; CA; CA²; ...; CAⁿ⁻¹] = n.\nBoth must hold for full state feedback and observer design."},
{id:198,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is time-domain specifications?",ans:"<strong>Rise time (tr):</strong> time to go from 10% to 90% of final value. <strong>Peak time (tp):</strong> time to first peak. <strong>Overshoot (Mp):</strong> maximum peak above final value (%). <strong>Settling time (ts):</strong> time to stay within ±2% (or ±5%) of final value. <strong>Delay time (td):</strong> time to reach 50%. These specs determine the required pole locations."},
{id:199,topic:"ctrl",q:"What is lead and lag compensation?",ans:"<strong>Lead compensator:</strong> adds positive phase at crossover → increases phase margin → faster response, better stability. G(s) = (s+z)/(s+p), z < p.\n<strong>Lag compensator:</strong> increases low-frequency gain → reduces steady-state error without significantly affecting stability. G(s) = (s+z)/(s+p), z > p.\nLead-lag combines both benefits."},

// ═══ Switchgear & Protection (Q200) ═══
{id:200,topic:"sgp",q:"What is a protective relay and its types?",ans:"A protective relay detects abnormal conditions and initiates tripping. <strong>Types:</strong>\n<strong>1. Overcurrent:</strong> Operates when current exceeds setting. Most common.\n<strong>2. Differential:</strong> Compares currents entering and leaving. For transformer/generator protection.\n<strong>3. Distance:</strong> Measures impedance to fault. For transmission line protection.\n<strong>4. Directional:</strong> Determines fault direction.\n<strong>5. Under-frequency:</strong> For load shedding.\n<strong>6. Buchholz:</strong> Gas-actuated for transformer internal faults.\nModern: Numerical relays (microprocessor-based, multi-function, communication-capable)."}
];
